  "bodyHtml": "<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\nHello!</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; margin: 0px; font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\nThank you for explaining your decisions!<br>\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; margin: 0px; font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\nThank you for at least considering adding CAPTCHA to mitigate large-scale attacks. However, this still leaves the form vulnerable to small-scale/targeted attacks.</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; margin: 0px; font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\nRegarding the accessibility argument (not everyone being skillful with IT) – the functionality could still retain clear user experience even with generic responses on the forms. The helpful situation-specific detail / instructions could instead be provided\n over email. For example, for new registration, the email could provide means for account activation, and for existing accounts, it could provide means for account recovery. Similarly, in case of changing emails and already existing account, you could explain\n the situation over email and provide account recovery options.</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\nConversely, I am curious, why the accessibility argument does not apply to the login form, being likely the most used from those tested. The login form currently does not reveal precise detail about what went wrong: \"See e-posti ja parooli kombinatsioon ei\n ole kasutuses\". Is there some other consideration for this behaviour? Similar observation holds for the password reset form.</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\nRegarding Gmail having similar flaws – we are aware of this.&nbsp;Google's public stance seems to be twofold:&nbsp;</div>\n<blockquote style=\"margin-left: 0.8ex; padding-left: 1ex; border-left: 3px solid rgb(200, 200, 200);\">\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<b>User enumeration.</b>&nbsp;Reports outlining user enumeration are not within scope unless you can demonstrate that we don't have any rate limits in place to protect our users.</div>\n</blockquote>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n(<a href=\"https://bughunters.google.com/about/rules/google-friends/6625378258649088/google-and-alphabet-vulnerability-reward-program-vrp-rules#non-qualifying-vulnerabilities\" id=\"OWAe66ec586-b561-131d-72dc-bbc36e3a2109\" class=\"OWAAutoLink elementToProof\" style=\"margin: 0px; text-align: left;\">source</a>)</div>\n<blockquote style=\"margin-left: 0.8ex; padding-left: 1ex; border-left: 3px solid rgb(200, 200, 200);\">\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\nWhen you sign up for a Google account and create a profile, your profile name is displayed in multiple locations and we generally allow other users who already know your email address or phone number to view your profile name. This approach is explained in\n our <a href=\"https://www.google.com/intl/en/policies/privacy/\" target=\"_blank\" id=\"OWA7874890e-1279-2057-5c7a-8dce33759035\" class=\"OWAAutoLink elementToProof\" rel=\"noopener\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\nPrivacy Policy</a>,</div>\n</blockquote>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n(<a href=\"https://bughunters.google.com/learn/invalid-reports/google-products/4983708328919040/ability-to-map-email-addresses-to-profile-names\" id=\"OWA2c112424-c5b2-1c80-e3c6-d035929616be\" class=\"OWAAutoLink\">source</a>)</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\nWe believe Google's approach still goes against GDPR, for example in case of small-scale/targeted attacks and especially for non-customers (those who have not agreed to their Privacy Policy), as they might not want to reveal they are not customers of Google.\n To be clear, while, email address providers do not have a feasible way to hide their customers – knowing the email address\n<code>@gmail.com</code>, it is obvious – it is still possible to create Google accounts with other emails.</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\nRegardless, they still seem interested in preventing large-scale attacks.</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\nRegarding vulnerabilities and responsibility of Piano, in context&nbsp;of GDPR, we understand ohtuleht.ee to be the data controller and Piano Inc to be the data processor (source:\n<a href=\"https://gdpr-info.eu/art-4-gdpr/\" id=\"OWA4d21fb1b-a762-8e8e-e0bd-a6f2f3cc97c7\" class=\"OWAAutoLink\">\nGDPR article 4 – Definitions</a>). We understand that it is the responsibility of the controller to ensure processing is performed in accordance with GDPR (source:\n<a href=\"https://gdpr-info.eu/art-24-gdpr/\" id=\"OWA93e2a1cb-c7c3-5ff4-d77b-c0b76dcdb610\" class=\"OWAAutoLink\">\nGDPR article 24 – Responsibility of the controller</a>).</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\n<br>\n</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\nBest regards,</div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\" style=\"font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\nGregor Eesmaa</div>\n<div id=\"appendonsend\"></div>",
